238. delapsae: i. e. swooping for a third attack, the first beginning at l. 225, and the second ll. 232—234.

curva: a customary epithet. Many adjectives in the ancient poets were attached generically to nouns, without any specific reference to the facts of the case. So in Homer a hero’s chief characteristic is mentioned with his name when there is no notion that it is displayed in some particular passage. So Achilles is ‘swift of foot‚' Odysseus ‘wily,' Hector ‘manslaying,’ and the like. So ships are ‘curved,’ the sea is ‘wine-dark‚’ διο. Vergil often imitates this use.
